# Debugging & Error Resolution

## Scope

Applies to ANY error surface: terminal/build output, Metro bundler logs,
TypeScript compiler errors, ESLint errors, runtime errors in the app
(crash logs, red screen, console errors), Supabase/RTK Query error
responses, and CI/test failures.

## Step 1 — Always triage before touching code

For any error encountered, first state:

1. Where it surfaced (terminal, app runtime, test, lint)
2. The actual error message/stack trace — quote it, don't paraphrase it
   away, since paraphrasing can hide the real signal
3. Which file/line is the likely root cause (not just where the error
   was thrown — a null reference often originates upstream of where it crashes)
4. Confidence level: certain / likely / uncertain

Never skip straight to a fix without this triage, even for "obvious" errors —
the triage is what prevents masking symptoms.

## Step 2 — Auto-resolve ONLY these categories, no confirmation needed

- TypeScript type errors with a single unambiguous fix (missing import,
  wrong prop type matching an existing interface, missing return type)
- ESLint/Prettier formatting and style violations
- Missing dependency causing a build failure — install it, but report
  what was installed and why
- A test failing due to a snapshot/assertion that's clearly stale
  relative to an intentional code change made in the same session
- Known, well-documented library errors with a single standard fix
  (e.g. a Metro cache issue solved by clearing cache)

After auto-resolving, report: what broke, what was changed, and why —
every time, even for trivial fixes. Silent fixes are not allowed.

## Step 3 — STOP and ask before resolving these

- Any error inside auth, payment, or RLS/policy logic, regardless of
  how simple the fix looks
- Any error where the fix would change existing behavior visible to
  a user (not just fixing a crash, but altering what the feature does)
- Any error where two or more plausible root causes exist — present
  the options and your read on which is more likely, then wait
- Any error that recurs after a previous "auto-resolve" attempt in
  this same session — a repeat means the first fix was wrong or
  incomplete; do not reapply the same category of fix twice without
  flagging that the approach isn't working
- Any runtime crash on a screen handling money, customer data, or
  role-gated access — these get a full root-cause writeup, not a patch

## Step 4 — No symptom-only patches

Banned patterns unless explicitly approved:

- Wrapping a crashing call in try/catch purely to suppress the crash
  without handling or surfacing the actual error
- Adding a null/undefined guard (`if (x)`, `x?.y`) as the entire fix
  without first explaining why x was null/undefined and confirming
  that's expected, not a symptom of a deeper bug
- Increasing a timeout to "fix" a race condition without investigating
  the race itself
- Catching and swallowing a Supabase/RTK Query error without logging
  or surfacing it somewhere visible

If a guard or try/catch IS the right fix (sometimes it is), say
explicitly why this is the correct fix and not a mask.

## Step 5 — Testing tied to the fix

- Any auto-resolved error in payment, auth, or RLS-adjacent code requires
  a regression test added in the same change, not deferred
- For other auto-resolved errors, add a test only if the bug could
  plausibly recur silently (e.g. an edge case in data formatting) —
  skip tests for pure formatting/lint fixes
- Never mark a fix "done" if `npm run build`, `tsc --noEmit`, and the
  existing test suite haven't all been run and passed after the change

## Step 6 — Recurring error tracking

If the same root cause (not just the same error message) appears more
than twice across a session, stop auto-resolving instances of it and
instead propose a structural fix — e.g. a missing type, a missing
shared validator, a missing RLS policy — rather than continuing to
patch each occurrence individually.

## Reporting format for every resolved error

Always state, in order: what broke → root cause → what changed →
what was verified (build/test/lint run) → anything still uncertain.
Never report "fixed" without the verification step actually having run.
